\subsection{Production Functions}
\label{sec:models}
%++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++


%------------------------------
\subsubsection{Cobb-Douglas production function}
\label{sec:CD}
%------------------------------

**** Go completely generic everywhere ($x_1$ instead of $k$). ****

The Cobb-Douglas production function 
is the canonical representation of indexed economic output ($y$) 
as a function of indexed factors of production~($x_1$, $x_2$, and $x_3$) and 
an additional exogenous, time-dependent term~($A$).
This production function can be expressed as
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:CD}
  y = \theta A \, {x_1}^{\alpha_1} \, {x_2}^{\alpha_2} \, {x_3}^{\alpha_3} \; ; \; A \equiv \mathrm{e}^{\lambda t},
\end{equation}
%
where 
$y \equiv Y/Y_{0}$,
$\theta$ is a scale parameter,
e is the base of the natural logarithm, 
$\lambda$ is represents the pace of technological progress,
$t$ is time measured in years,
$x_1 = k \equiv K/K_{0}$, 
$x_2 = l \equiv L/L_{0}$, 
$x_3 = e \equiv E/E_{0}$, 
$Y$ is economic output represented by GDP, 
$K$ is capital stock expressed in currency units, 
$L$ is labor expressed in workers or work-hours/year, 
$E$ is energy expressed in units of energy per time, typically TJ/year, and
0 subscripts indicate values at an initial year.
All historical data~($y$, $k$, $l$, and $e$) are indexed (by ratio)
relative to an initial year. 
Time~($t$) is indexed (by difference) relative to an initial year.
After indexing, $\theta$ is expected to be near unity,
but no other parameters change.%
  \footnote{Dimensionless, indexed quantities are represented by lower-case symbols 
  ($y$, $x$, $k$, $l$, and $e$), 
  and dimensional quantities are represented by upper-case symbols 
  ($Y$, $K$, $L$, and $E$). 
  Model parameters are represented by Greek letters
  ($\theta$, $\lambda$, $\alpha_1$, $\alpha_2$, $\alpha_3$, and
  later $\delta_1$, $\delta$, $\sigma_1$, and $\sigma$).} 

The parameters $\alpha_1$, $\alpha_2$, and $\alpha_3$ are output elasticities
that indicate the marginal productivity of 
$x_1$, $x_2$, and $x_3$ in the economy, respectively.
Typically, the constraint $\alpha_1 + \alpha_2 + \alpha_3 = 1$ is assumed, 
indicating constant returns to scale.


%------------------------------
\subsubsection{Constant Elasticity of Substitution Production Function (CES)} 
\label{sec:CES}
%------------------------------

The Constant Elasticity of Substitution~(CES) model 
is given as
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:CESgeneric}
  y = \theta \: A \: \left\{\delta B_1^{\rho/\rho_1} 
      + (1-\delta) x_3^{-\rho} \right\}^{-1/\rho}; 
      A \equiv \mathrm{e}^{\lambda t},
\end{equation}
%
where
$B_1 \equiv \delta_1 x_1^{-\rho_1} + (1-\delta_1) x_2^{-\rho_1}$, and
$x_1$, $x_2$, and $x_3$ are factors of production
and permutations of capital~($k$), labor~($l$), and energy~($e$).
The $(kl)e$ nesting has $x_1 = k$, $x_2 = l$, and $x_3 = e$; 
the $(le)k$ nesting has $x_1 = l$, $x_2 = e$, and $x_3 = k$; and
the $(ek)l$ nesting has $x_1 = e$, $x_2 = k$, and $x_3 = l$.

For the CES function, 
output elasticities~($\alpha_1$, $\alpha_2$, and $\alpha_3$) are not constant;
rather, they vary with factors of production ($x_1$, $x_2$, and $x_3$) over time.
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:alpha_1}
  \alpha_1 \equiv
  \frac{ \frac{\partial y}{\partial x_1} }
          { \frac{y}{x_1} } 
  = 
  \frac{ \delta  \delta _1 x_1^{-\rho _1} B_1^{ ( \frac{\rho}{\rho_1}-1 ) }  }
  { \delta B_1^{ ( \frac{\rho }{\rho_1} ) } + (1 - \delta) x_3^{-\rho }}
\end{equation}
%

\begin{equation} \label{eq:alpha_2}
  \alpha_2 \equiv \frac{ \frac{\partial y}{\partial x_2} }{\frac{y}{x_2}} =
  \frac{ \delta  \left(1-\delta _1 \right) x_2^{-\rho _1} B_1^{ ( \frac{\rho }{\rho _1}-1 ) } }
  { \delta B_1^{ ( \frac{\rho }{\rho_1} ) } + (1 - \delta) x_3^{-\rho }}
\end{equation}
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:alpha_3}
  \alpha_3 \equiv \frac{ \frac{\partial y}{\partial x_3} }{ \frac{y}{x_3} } =  
      \frac{1 - \delta}{\delta  x_3^{\rho } B_1^{(\frac{\rho }{\rho_1} ) } + 1 - \delta}
\end{equation}
%
It can be verified that
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:sum_betas}
  \alpha_1 + \alpha_2 + \alpha_3 = 1 \; .
\end{equation}

Similar to the output elasticities, 
the elasticity of substitution between factors of production $x_1$ and $x_2$~($\sigma_{1,2}$) 
is time-varying and given by the Allen-Uzawa elasticity of substitution:
%
\begin{equation} \label{eq:sigma_1_2}
  \sigma_{1,2} = \frac{ (1 - \rho_1)^{-1} - (1-\rho)^{-1}}{\delta \left( \frac{y}{B_1^{-\frac{1}{\rho_1}}} \right) ^ {1 + \rho}}
                      + (1 + \rho)^{-1} \; .
\end{equation}
